76561197995436318,Recommended,253630,8345350,"Posted: 27 December, 2013",all,Twitchblade,"Steam Marines is a game about how hard it would be if you were responsible for protecting a ship from robots and/or aliens, but you forgot to pack a map.Steam Marines is a roguelike (pedants be damned) mixed with ""classical"" squad based tactical gameplay, hitting a good balance of both genres.  The core of the game is about managing a team of 4 Marines are you move through a procedurally generated ship, combating a variety of enemies in turn based combat.  You clear the ship room by room, exercising the best tactics you can to conserve life and ammo so you can make it to the next floor.  There's an AP system in place, so on your turn, you move your squad around as far as your AP will let you, and then it's the enemy's turn, exhausting their AP, etc. so positioning and attention to detail is required to make sure you don't leave a Marine stranded in a bad positionI've never strayed past normal difficulty, but even there the game can be pretty unforgiving.  Death is permanent, and often swift.  Ammo is limited and so is inventory space, so you really need to scrounge carefully and decide on what to pack when you move between decks.  I've had games that were rougher than others, but never once did I feel as if the RNG was the sole thing that screwed me over- in most of my games, there was something better I could've done to avoid calamity.Despite being an early access title, I wholly recommend Steam Marines.  Even in its current alpha state, the game is a lot of fun and tactically challenging, and as an added bonus, the developer is really active with the Steam community.What I paid for it: 10 bucks.What I would pay for it: Upon completion, 15 bucks, easy.At the time of this review, the most recent build was v0.8.4a"
