,Recommended,253630,8377282,"Posted: 28 December, 2013",all,thorvindr,"This is a review of an early-access game. This game has not technically been ""released"" yet. You are paying to playtest and report bugs/problems. In return, you get a copy of the game when it's released. I have given this game a thumbs up because I think it has potential, not because I think you should buy it. If you don't want to playtest a game in development, DON'T BUY THIS GAME.As I said, I think this game has potential But right now, the word is ""simplistic."" And in this context, that's a bad word.The gist is, you get a squad of four space marines of various classes, and you fight through several decks of a derelict space ship. Every turn, each marine gets a certain number of action points. Moving one square costs one action point, shooting costs one action point, turning 90 degrees costs one action point, reloading your weapon costs all your remaining action points.That gets very frustrating, very quickly, but I could live with it. what I CAN'T live with is the aiming mechanic. You can only fire at an enemy that is DIRECTLY in front of you. So if the enemy is four squares north and one square west, your first shot is going to cost three points (move one west, turn north, fire). Not only does that make the game difficult, but it also makes it very frustrating.That on top of the fact that realoading your weapon ends that marine's turn makes this game (for me) essentially unplayable in its current form. There are a lot of nifty ideas in this game, but for now that is preventing me from enjoying it.But take heart! This is a pre-release game, so it will be getting better. I can't say for sure that the things I don't like will get fixed, but I am optimistic that Steam Marines will be a fine game some day.EDIT:Just started playing this game again, and I'm enjoying it thoroughly. Reading my review above, I can't say that any of that has changed (though unchecking the option for ""facing costs AP"" was a big relief), but it seems that it matters less. Another problem that I had before was that it was hard to see. Once a marine looked away from a wall (for example), I seem to recall that there was no placeholder graphic to remind you ""hey! There was a wall here!"" Now walls don't disappear when you're not looking at them. I could be remembering wrong, but if that was a problem before it no longer is.This is now a game that I will whole-heartedly recommend."
