,Recommended,253630,14875755,"Posted: 13 March, 2015",all,Vinrafel,"Steam Marines is a very fun and very difficult game. I enjoyed it a lot, despite the fact that I've only made it past the first section once.Video Review:https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=G4_ibJzI9F0What is it?Steam Marines is a rouge-like turn based strategy game. It's gameplay most closely resembles the old Space Hulk board game (also the more recent games of the same name). Every time you start you get to choose four soldiers, each of which has a class and a perk. You then enter a randomly generated space ship that is infested with evil robots. Your goal is to fight your way to the elevator and get to the next floor.There are five different decks of the ship that you have to go through. Each of these decks is divided into five levels with a boss on the final level. You always start on one deck, but you then get to choose where you go after you complete it. Each deck has its own asthetic and set of enemies that goes with it.Throughout the game, your soldiers will level up, thereby gaining skills and abilities, as well as get new equipment. This adds good depth to the later game (and probably stops you from being completely curb-stomped).I thought I might also note that if you have a less then four soldiers in your squad at the end of a floor you have a chance of getting a new soldier. You don't get to choose the class or perk, but this can at least give you a fighting chance if things don't go too well.Pros:-The game has a good variety of classes. In saying this, I mean that each class has a distinct role in the squad because of their specific weapon.-The enemies feel equal to your soldiers. In my opinion, a squad turn based strategy needs enemies that are on a similar level to your soldiers. Without that, it would either be so easy that you don't have to think tactically, or far too hard. Steam Marines strikes a nice balance.-There are distinct enemies. Through my journey I've seen enemies that are pure melee, pure range, ones that lose AP as you hit them, and ones that can't be damages from cenrtain sides. Each of these enemies needs to be dealt with using different tactics, which adds a good depth to the game.-Each deck has a difficulty rating. You might think that this doesn't mean that much, of course they do that just makes sense. You're right, it does make sense, but the permadeath makes that addition all the more important. You will know which deck is least likely to kill you and thereby least likely to lose you all of your hard work.Cons:-The random generation sometimes causes problems. It is possible to enter a level on that levels elevator. One would think that that would be a good thing, but there is a problem. The boss on the final level spawns on the elevator. The first time I made it to level five I spawned on the elevator, directly next to the boss. This is an almost guaranteed loss.-This con is not necessarily bad for everyone, but it still needs to be noted. The game is VERY difficult. I've played nine hours of the game and I only made it past the first deck once.-The system for executing the enemy turns is flawed. Firstly, on default settings the enemy turn will last an ungodly length of time. This can be easily fixed in the settings, but there is a bigger issue. The game has a setting that, in essence, focuses on the screen as the enemies move. It will do this not only for ones that you can see, but also enemies that you can't see around you. This gives you advanced warning of where enemies are. Turning this off means that it will NEVER follow enemy movements. Your screen is also locked in place while the enemy moves. I hope you kept all of squad together, or you won't get to watch the action. (Man, that was long winded)The game has some flaws, but overall I enjoyed it a lot. If you have played Dark Souls (and are hardnened to the idea of constant death) and enjoy squad turn-based strategy games then this game will hit the mark. It's a lot of deadly fun for $15."
